Chip Shortage - August 2023


Things were bad, they got a bit better, and now they look worse. Lead times on chips are now 12 months. I got lucky before with checking and ordering smaller quantities, but companies like Mouser are no longer selling to small-volume consumers, only large OEM companies. I should have enough now to last until November/December depending on orders.


Megadesk


Megadesk is an AVR based, open source, drop in controller for the IKEA Bekant standing desks.


The Bekant is a relatively inexpensive motorized standing desk. It doesn't come with memory positions.


I wanted to have memory positions for easily switching between various work positions. I also didn't want to be limited to just 2 positions. However, as I went through the process, I realized the hardest part was designing the enclosure. 3D Printing is a great option, but lacks that professional look, and limits the availability to those with printers. Additionally, getting custom membrane buttons that would look good was also extremely expensive. Simple push-buttons would take away from the look of the desk.


By targeting the factory enclosure, it keeps the original look and robustness, while adding functionality.


Fully Assembled


All assembled versions are programmed and tested before shipping. See my testing rig in action!


Installation


I now have a video covering some tips on installation. You can also read through some of the reviews below for user tips.


Some units now have a latch for the ribbon cable. It can be opened simply with a fingernail with very little force before sliding in the ribbon cable, and then pushing the latch back down to close.


Operation


    

  • Holding Up/Down moves the desk just like the OEM version.
    • 

  • Memory recall is done by short clicking the UP button. To recall memory position 3, you would push the up button 3 times. 3 beeps will be played back (representing memory position 3), and the desk will move to that position.
    • 

  • Memory store is done by clicking the UP button for the memory position you wish to save, but HOLDING the last click. To save memory position 3, you would push the up button twice rapidly, and on the 3rd press, hold it until 3 beeps are heard. The number of beeps represents which memory position it saved in.
    • 

  • There is no practical limit to the number of memory, although the AVR will have a hard limit if you get into the tens of positions. (Memory #1 does not exist, as holding the UP button is for moving the desk manually)
    • 

  • Any button can be pushed at any time to interrupt movement during a memory recall.
    • 



Assembly


Unplug the existing controller from the desk.


You will need to carefully pry apart the grey plastic enclosure. It has 3-4 attachment points, after that it is fairly easy. Scoring the seams with a sharp blade can help. Also, once re-assembled, the topside portion will not be visible, so minor cosmetic damage will not be seen.


Carefully remove the ribbon cable from the existing connector.


Connect the cable to the header. The red wire goes to the same side as the flat ribbon cable. Reversing the connector will not cause damage to the unit - it will simply not power up.


Carefully insert the flat ribbon cable into the megadesk board, ensuring it is seated as far back as possible.


Connect the control unit back to the desk. When power is applied, you should hear a series of 4 beeps, rising in tone.


Test out the buttons, and enjoy having near-unlimited memory positions on your desk! You can use a small piece of tape or a dab of adhesive to keep the lid on the control unit, but it will be held in place once screwed back on the desk.


Troubleshooting


Please view the steps on github


Live in the UK?


Consider the ultimate work surface for your standing desk with a handmade solid custom sized hardwood desk/table top.

This is perfection

      
      

        Firstly, it arrived so quickly. UK delivery was in 4 days!

Same as everyone says, getting the top of the desk's control unit off is painful. It's got multiple long inner joins, I cracked a lot of mine but as it all ends up hidden I don't care. Just keep jamming a small screwdriver in sand pry it up. Work from the corners next to the cable, this makes sure you avoid the area with the ribbon cable.

The unit itself is easy to install. There's even a note on the board itself telling you where the red wire should go, making that step even easier. Follow Greg's video for help getting the ribbon cable back in.

Now that it's firmware got updated to let it perform the calibration steps, you don't need to keep the old board, although I have.

Very easy to use, it's literally the simplest functionality. Greg has made a great product and you should definitely buy one if you're on the fence.

His GitHub page has plenty of documentation.

Love it, great purchase. Nice one Greg.

Worst exactly as described

      
      

        Worst exactly as described and it arrived safely (Canada > Miami,FL > Dominican Republic). Opening the Ikea control was difficult because it's welded shut, but that was fairly warned on the installation video. So no surprises there. What I ended up doing was taking a chunk off the side with an Exacto knife until I finally saw a glimpse of the inside. Then, I simply pried it off. 

Thank you so much for this product!

FANTASTIC UPGRADE Easier to open than feared with right tool

      
      

        SO SO SO glad that google took me to this fantastic desk upgrade. Using two button mode I now have double tap down to sit, double tap up to stand, its just what the Ikea should have done. If you are reading this wondering whether to buy - HELL YES.

Greg is a genius - all you need to do is open the unit (see notes below) swap over the circuit board, a replacement wire is supplied and buttons connect with a small ribbon cable that's easy to connect, sorted !

UK shipping - just SEVEN days.

The elephant in the room, opening the damned unit, lots easier than I thought and afterwards, once you push the bent plastic back with the shaft of a screwdriver, there is only a slight whiteish line at the top to say anything ever happened. For me the secret was as below, took just 5 minutes, don't touch anything else (don't go around all the other edges for example, not needed, doesn't help and causes unnecessary damage).
1. Just using a sharp thin blade open up the gap at the back near the corner away from the wire.
2. Insert a 2-3 mm screwdriver (I used one of those mains checker ones that has a neon light inside for mains voltage warning), you will need to push down and under the top cover, it will make some damage, but like I said above, afterwards its hardly visible. You need to work it in and lever open the top until just that corner snaps open. You are now home and dry !
3. Work around the sides snapping open first the near side then the far side.

Works great! Easy to install! Definitely would recommened

      
      

        For the life of me i do not understand why IKEA does not currently sell a desk with the ability to set height profiles.

Thankfully this exists. Easy to install and works great.
- quick presses recalls that heigh profile (2 press for profile 2, 3 presses for 3)
- quick presses then a long press to set that profile to the current height

Izipizi. Hardest part about it is prying off the back plate to the controller housing, check out his video above on how to do that.

It looks like on his video that the ribbon cable sits very far into the port, but mine couldnt go very far in. But I was able to lock it in proply with the small latch.

Oh and don't be like me and forget to put the plastic key back in and wonder why it doesnt work lol.

took about a couple weeks to get to me in Australia.
